{'symptoms': '**Diabetes**\n\nDiabetes is a chronic disease that affects how your body turns food into energy. There are two main types of diabetes: type 1 and type 2.\n\n**Symptoms of diabetes**\n\nThe symptoms of diabetes can vary depending on the type of diabetes you have.\n\n**Type 1 diabetes**\n\nThe symptoms of type 1 diabetes usually develop suddenly and can include:\n\n* Feeling very thirsty\n* Needing to urinate more often than usual\n* Blurred vision\n* Feeling tired\n* Losing weight unintentionally\n\n**Type 2 diabetes**\n\nThe symptoms of type 2 diabetes can be mild and may take many years to be noticed. Symptoms may be similar to those of type 1 diabetes but are often less marked. As a result, the disease may be diagnosed several years after onset, after complications have already arisen.\n\n**Over time, diabetes can damage blood vessels in the heart, eyes, kidneys and nerves.**\n\nPeople with diabetes have a higher risk of health problems including heart attack, stroke and kidney failure. Diabetes can cause permanent vision loss by damaging blood vessels in the eyes. Many people with diabetes develop problems with their feet from nerve damage and poor blood flow.', 'treatments': '**Common treatments for diabetes:**\n\n* **Lifestyle changes:** Maintaining a healthy lifestyle is crucial for managing diabetes. This includes eating a balanced diet, exercising regularly, and maintaining a healthy weight.\n* **Medications:** Some people with type 2 diabetes may need to take medications to help manage their blood sugar levels. These medications can include:\n    * Metformin\n    * Sulfonylureas\n    * Sodium-glucose co-transporters type 2 (SGLT-2) inhibitors\n* **Insulin injections:** People with type 1 diabetes need insulin injections for survival.\n* **Other medications:** Along with medications to lower blood sugar, people with diabetes often need medications to lower their blood pressure and statins to reduce the risk of complications.', 'causes': "The provided information does not contain any details about the common causes of diabetes. Therefore, I cannot answer the user's query.", 'source': {'https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/diabetes'}}